fields.intro: There are three main data types we will look at in this module. They are Strings, Numbers and Booleans.
fields.visual_1_1: The first graphic shows us the variable name, which has a data type of string. Strings are simply plaintext which are enclosed inside either double or single quotation marks.
fields.visual_1_2: Next we see numbers, as you can see, there is no need for quotation marks. Numbers can be stored in variables as whole numbers (integers) or decimal numbers (floats). In Python 3 there is no explicitly define limit to how large an integer value can be.
fields.visual_1_3: Finally we take a look at booleans. Booleans represent one of two values : True or False

fields.intro: Python programs have control structures which direct the order of execution of the statements in the program. Let's look at one of the fundamental parts of Python programming - if and if...else statements.
fields.active_1_1: Be careful with indentation. In Python, the body of the if statement is indicated by the indentation. The body starts with an indentation and the first unindented line marks the end.
fields.visual_1_1: In our flowchart, we can see the path a program takes a certain path. If the condition is true, the block of code in the 'if block' will be executed. But if the condition is false, it skips to the code outside of the else block.  Check out the example in code below.
fields.visual_1_2: The if..else statement evaluates test expression and will execute the body of if only when the test condition is True. If the condition is False, the body of else is executed. This can be extremely useful when you need to run some code ONLY if the statement is false.
